Different octane numbers of gasoline indicate the degree of its oxidation, that is, the ratio of the amount of oxygen in the molecule to the amount of carbon. This parameter is used to characterize the quality of gasoline, as a higher oxidation index indicates lower hydrocarbon contents and higher carbon oxide contents, leading to reduced engine performance and fuel efficiency.

The octane number is expressed in digits from 0 to 9. Small numbers denote a low oxidation index and correspond to lower hydrocarbon contents, while large numbers indicate a high oxidation index and correspond to higher carbon oxide contents.

Classifying gasoline by octane numbers, it can be said that:

• 0-3 classes: low-octane gasoline (usually used in sports cars);
• 4-6 classes: mid-octane gasoline (usually used in passenger cars);
• 7-9 classes: high-octane gasoline (usually used in sports cars).

